QUESTION1: media query and their use
Media queries is used to set the viewport according to the user's screen.
The content of the website can easily and properly view in different screen of the user.
Such as mobile, desktop etc.
It make user interactive, enhance the performance.
Media queries are a feature of CSS that allow you to conditionally apply styles based on a set of browser .
It make a website more responsive.
Some commonly used media features are mentioned below.

Orientation
Resolution
Aspect ratio
Width
Height

SYNTAX:  @media screen, print {
  /* … */
}

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
QUESTION2: min-width and max-width

Min-width define the minimum width of screen in which media query is applied.
Max-width define the maximum width of the scrren in whicc media query is applied.

@media (min-width: 700px) { … } -  browser’s viewport width equal or wider than 700px;
@media (max-width: 700px) { … } -  browser’s viewport width equal or narrower than 700px.

        @media(min-width:600px)and(max-width:900px){
        background-color:red;
        }

Means when screen color is minimum 600px  and maximum color is color is 900 then background color changed into red.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Question3: float
It specifies how an element should float.(right,left,none,inherit).

left - The element floats to the left of its container
right - The element floats to the right of its container
none - The element does not float . It is default value.
inherit - The element inherits the float value of its parents.

<html>
    <head>
        <style>
              .class1{
                        float:right;
                     }
        </style>
    </head>
    <body>
        <p class="class1">Hello I am saloni kansal</p>
        
    </body>
   </html>
  The content of the p tag will be display in right side.
=======================================================================
clear
It specifies what should happen with the element that is next to a floating element.
none - The element is not pushed below left or right floated elements. It is default value.
left - The element is pushed below left floated elements
right - The element is pushed below right floated elements
both - The element is pushed below both left and right floated elements
inherit - The element inherits the clear value from its parents.

<html>
<head>
      <style>
            .div3 {
  float: left;
  padding: 10px;  
  border: 3px solid #73AD21;
}

.div4 {
  padding: 10px;
  border: 3px solid red;
  clear: left;
}
      </style>
      
<body>    
<div class="div3">Hi</div>
<div class="div4"> Hello</div>

</body>
</html>
